<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1937-09-18T07:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1937-09-18T07:00:00-05:00" n="690" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d690">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94111/60: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Nanking</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-09-18T20:00:00+08:00">September 18, 1937—8
                                    p.m.</date><lb/>[Received September 18—1:22 p.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>683. Department’s 239, September 15, 8 p.m. During a visit with the
                            Minister for Foreign Affairs<note n="25" xml:id="d690fn25">Wang
                                Chung-hui.</note> this morning I introduced the subject of
                            President’s order and explained situation along the line of <pb facs="0544" n="536" xml:id="pg_536"/> views expressed by the
                            Department. Doctor Wang said that Chinese Government was deeply
                            disappointed at interruption of shipment of materials. He stated that in
                            the light of the mandatory character of the Neutrality Act he
                            appreciated attitude and moderate action taken.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Johnson</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
